    const update = () => {
        timeRef.current = performance.now();
    };
    const id = setInterval(update, 16);
    return () => clearInterval(id);
}, []);
```

The cleanup `return () => clearInterval(id)` IS present. This interval is properly cleaned up on unmount. Not a bug.

---

### Bug 8 (CONFIRMED, HIGH CONFIDENCE): Docking detection in `tick()` runs with the SNAPSHOT value of `dockState` from the top of the tick, but the magnet-to-approaching transition at line 339 reads `dockingStateRef.current` live — meaning it can transition even when `dockState` (the local snapshot) is `'magnet'` but `dockingStateRef.current` was set to `'none'` mid-tick by the disengage-on-target-change block at line 334

**File:** `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\Universe\hooks\useRocketMode.js`, lines 108 and 334-356

```js
const dockState = dockingStateRef.current;  // line 108 — snapshot
...
// Disengage magnet if best target changes (line 334)
if (dockingStateRef.current === 'magnet' && bestIdx !== dockingTargetIdxRef.current) {
    dockingStateRef.current = 'none';       // live write
    dockingTargetIdxRef.current = -1;
}
// Transition magnet → approaching (line 339)
if (dockingStateRef.current === 'magnet') { // reads live ref, correct
```

The transition at line 339 correctly reads the live ref, not the snapshot. So if the disengage block at line 334 sets it to `'none'`, the transition block at line 339 will see `'none'` (not `'magnet'`) and correctly skip. This is safe.

However, look at the magnet auto-aim block at line 132:

```js
if (dockState === 'magnet') {   // uses snapshot from line 108
```

This runs using the OLD snapshot. If dockingStateRef was changed to `'none'` between frame start and this point (which can't happen within a single synchronous tick — there's no async here), but since tick is synchronous, `dockState` from line 108 is consistent for the duration of the tick. This is fine.

---

### Bug 9 (CONFIRMED, HIGH CONFIDENCE): The `dockingStateRef.current === 'done'` state is never reset before the next `enter()` or `restoreFromSnapshot()` call — but both functions DO reset it explicitly (lines 386, 551). However `exit()` does NOT reset it (lines 479-484)

**File:** `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\Universe\hooks\useRocketMode.js`, lines 464-485

```js
const exit = useCallback(() => {
    isActiveRef.current = false;
    ...
    dockingStateRef.current = 'none';  // line 479 — IS reset
```

Actually `exit()` does reset it to `'none'` at line 479. Let me re-read:

```
479→        dockingStateRef.current = 'none';
480→        dockingTargetIdxRef.current = -1;
481→        dockingProgressRef.current = 0;
482→        dockingStarScaleRef.current = 1;
483→        inputFrozenRef.current = false;
